        "username": "6vbz6d8ooppxhw1a",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/6/ce7236/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-05-22T19:55:04.815Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Now that you’ve proven that it’s possible to do this on Windows, due to Recall, I feel like it should be obvious that users would want there to be protection for preventing their conversations from falling into the wrong hands were they to use your app on a compromised device.</p>\n<p>Now, obviously this is going to introduce some trade-offs, but that’s precisely why you simply allow them to disable the protected mode, should they require it. Better yet, get to work and add the accessibility and back up features straight into your application so that users aren’t limited to using questionable third-party solutions which may not do things like, encrypt the backups and screenshots, or… I don’t know… NOT send all your text to speech activity straight to Google, Microsoft, or whoever!</p>\n<p>So, how about giving us those features built into your app, and in such a way as to actually protect your users from compromises? Do you think you can handle that?</p>\n<p>Oh! But, why stop at HDCP? Why not also include TEMPEST fonts to prevent Electromagnetic Eavesdropping? Oh yeah! You knew that it’s totally possible to read the contents of your computer display through “Unintentional Emanations” which travel right through solid concrete walls, didn’t you?  And, scientific experiments confirm the effectiveness of TEMPEST fonts to prevent such electromagnetic infiltration.</p>\n<p>See here:<br>\n<a href=\"https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/10/8/2828\" class=\"onebox\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/10/8/2828</a></p>\n<p>And here:<br>\n<a href=\"https://www.ntt-review.jp/archive/ntttechnical.php?contents=ntr200810sf2.html\" class=\"onebox\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://www.ntt-review.jp/archive/ntttechnical.php?contents=ntr200810sf2.html</a></p>",
